Good  examples here are university rankings  (e.g., the Academ ic Ranking of World Universities , see  http://www.shanghairanking.com ), which are mostly  based on bibliometric measure s, but  additionally include further  indicators (such as the number of Nobel laureates ) to assess  research performanc e. Research on the ecological rationality of heuristics can inform  prescriptions and recommendations: The International Soci ety for Informetrics  and Scientometrics (ISSI) – the international association of scholars and  professionals active in the interdisciplinary study science of science, science  communication, and science policy (see http://www.issi -society.org) – could  publi sh a list of well -studied heuristics (an adaptive toolbox for the use of  bibliometrics) alongside with the environments for which there is evidence that  those heuristics lead to accurate decisions (Bornmann & Marx, in pr ess).

How is it possible that certain biblio metric indicators, such as the journal  impact factor , remain  instruments of research evaluations although prominent and popular  declarations, such as the Declaration on Research Assessment  (DORA , see https://sfdora.org ),  exist against its use?
